entry.title: [DBSC] Add enterprise policy controlling feature state
entry.content:
This CL adds a new "DeviceBoundSessionCredentialsEnabled" policy that

gives enterprises control over DBSC feature state. Following the best

practice from [1], the enterprise setting takes precedence over the

feature value.



`switches::IsBoundSessionCredentialsEnabled()` helper function was

modified to take into account the policy value. As a PrefService object

is required to check the policy value, it's no longer possible to call

`switches::IsBoundSessionCredentialsEnabled()` from a renderer process.

Luckily, renderers can infer the DBSC state from other parameter passed

by the browser through Mojo.



Interesting to note that "DeviceBoundSessionCredentialsEnabled" is

configured as a per-profile policy meaning that different profiles

might have different feature states.



[1] https://www.chromium.org/developers/enterprise-changes/#2-give-enterprises-control

entry.title: win: Fix vsync when trying to WaitForVSync on a stale DXGI factory
entry.content:
When a DXGI factory becomes stale, WaitForVSync on its adapters' outputs

will not actually wait for VSync. This causes us to go into

the "WaitForVSync sleep" mode, which takes slightly longer than our

intended interval, causing us to drop our framerate. This can happen

when a user disconnects and reconnects to an RDP session with a running

chromium instance.



This CL makes it so when we detect that the factory is stale, we create

a new DXGI factory for the purpose of finding an output on and adapter

matching the LUID of the previous adapter. We no longer cache the

HMONITOR because there is no guarantee that an HMONITOR will remain

valid after we query it.

entry.title: Add NearbyConnectionsManager::ClearIncomingPayloadWithId().
entry.content:
The data migration project (linked in the bug's description) may

transfer thousands of bytes and file payloads in one session. On

top of that there may be bytes payloads sent in parallel with other

file payloads.



Currently, the only method available is ClearIncomingPayloads()

which erases every single payload that's been received thus far.

The data migration project requires a more fine-grained method to

erase specific payloads as it processes them (or we'll have consumed

a lot of memory and file descriptors as the session goes on). That's

the method being added in this CL.

entry.content:
Since a CompositeMatcher can only be associated with exactly one

extension, add the extension id field to the class, so that in

RequestParams, the allow_rule_max_priority map can be keyed by

extension id instead of a pointer to a CompositeMatcher. This is safer

if the map will be used between request phases as currently the

CompositeMatcher gets deleted if the extension unloads, which will

invalidate the map's key.



This CL has no behavior change.

entry.title: Reapply "Enable Widevine CDM rollback on Linux/ChromeOS"
entry.content:
This reverts commit b1646bfdf2c9f2bbe91c5124ea20deb92793c38d.



This change was reverted due to problems with LaCros. Reapplying with a

flag so that it doesn't by default apply to LaCros. If the flag is

disabled then the previous behavior is maintained (choose the Component

Updated version only if it is greater than the bundled version.)



Original change's description:

> Enable Widevine CDM rollback on Linux/ChromeOS

>

> Component Update allows for downgrading components to an earlier

> version. However, on Linux and ChromeOS, the Widevine CDM needs

> to be loaded before the zygote is locked, and thus uses a hint

> file to determine which version is supplied by Component Update.

> Current checking in cdm_registration uses the larger of the bundled

> version or the Component Updated version (if both exist), so if the

> downgrade is to a version prior to the current bundled version, the

> rollback doesn't work.

>

> To fix this, the hint file created when a new component is downloaded

> is updated to keep track of the bundled version at the time it was

> downloaded, as Component Update will check the bundled version when

> determining if a new version is required. If the bundled version

> matches this saved version, then the bundled version is skipped when

> checking what should be loaded into the zygote (thus always loading

> the Component Updated version).



Bug: 41491028

Test: manual test plus updated unit_tests pass

entry.title: Don't sign out for non-auth signaling errors
entry.content:
We've received reports that users can't connect to machines which are

experiencing a high number of network change events. It looks like

this is because the FtlSignalStrategy class is signing the user out

and back in for every network error.



The FtlRegistrationManager has its own logic for updating the FTL

auth token when it is about to expire and handles network errors

independently so we don't need to explicitly sign the user out for

retriable network errors.



One concern would be whether fixing this will result in a different

service API returning RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED since the host will

need to re-establish a signaling channel and report both offline

and online status to our backend. I tested this change using a

timer which disconnected the signaling channel every 30 seconds for

several hours and did not encounter any issues with signaling.

entry.title: Adjust GLTextureImageBacking scanout/upload usage
entry.content:
GLTextureImageBacking wasn't used for shared memory GMBs, aka when it

had SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_CPU_UPLOAD on Android. This isn't a real

limitation it's just that shared memory GMBs are only used on Android

for one-copy raster and SharedMemoryImageBacking is used for that case.

Remove the limitation but make sure that GLTextureImageBacking rejects

SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_SCANOUT on Android always since it's not

grandfathered into allowing it. Also start rejecting scanout usage on

Mac since IOSurfaceImageBacking actually support it and should always be

available.
